charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Hi guys 👋, 

Thank you for visiting my fundraising page. 

Plan of action is to RUN 100KM in March!  Macmillan is a charity very close to my heart. I've seen just how much Macmillan support people going through such a hard time. 

There's so many ways Macmillan support cancer patients, from help financially helping with holidays, wigs, everyday bills but also emotionally. They become a friend to patients, a helping hand and are ALWAYS there at the other end of the phone. - It really amazes me. 

So it really is an honour just to have an opportunity to fund raise for this charity. 

So please guys, let's donate as much as we can! I will be keeping you all updated! 


Thank you, keep safe ❤

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit this JustGiving page.

MacMillan Cancer Support were with April from diagnosis through to her last days.  They provided support in the early days, a short holiday at one of their holiday homes in Filey which she was able to enjoy with her family in the summer last year and care at home when she left the hospice.

This has  been a year when charities have really struggled with donations so this will really help bolster their finances.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
TechLabs London employees are walking 50 miles throughout the month of March to raise much needed funds for Macmillan Cancer Support. 

Friends and family members of employees are also taking part in a bid to beat the winter blues, get fitter and raise funds for a worthy cause. 

Please show your support by making a donation of any size to help this incredibly important Charity continue their hard work in the fight against Cancer. 

Macmillan Cancer Support is one of the largest British charities and provides specialist health care, information and financial support to people affected by cancer. It also looks at the social, emotional and practical impact cancer can have, and campaigns for better cancer care. Macmillan Cancer Support's goal is to reach and improve the lives of everyone who has cancer in the UK.

story:
Carolyn was a much loved, wife, mother, mother in law, Nan and friend who lost her short battle with spleen cancer on 18th February 2021 at home with her family. 

If you would like to make a donation to Macmillan Cancer Support in memory of Carolyn you can do so here.  The Macmillan nurses were a great support to Carolyn and they have always been a charity close to her heart.  

The family would like to thank everyone for their support and kind words at this difficult and very sad time.

Ivan, Julie, David, Richard & Laura

story:
Cancer affects everyone in one way or another. 

Recently its affected my family. 

My grans battled cancer once, and is now battling again. 

My auntie battled cancer and sadly passed a few years back.

Cancer sucks. 

I'm here to try and raise a few quid for macmillan, it's the least I can do. 

I've decided for March I'm going to run at least 25 miles (due to injury I don't want to set it too high but will do more if I can) if knee injury plays up again I'll switch to 25 hours of fitness instead lol. 

But also I'm ditching the biscuits, I'm ditching the sweets and chocolate (except my shakes lol). 

Here goes 🤦🏻‍♀️

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Hello, we are planning to walk part of the Norfolk Coastal Path from Hunstanton to Mundesley (44miles, 71km) in memory of our wonderful Mum who passed away on 2nd August 2020. 

Mum was diagnosed in March 2020 with a rare form of melanoma skin cancer which appeared on the sole of her foot. When Mum passed away in August, it had subsequently spread to her lymph nodes, lungs, liver and bone. In Mum’s months of illness she had several operations, immunotherapy and care in both Whiston and St Helens Hospitals and Nobles Hospital, Isle of Man. Mum’s care was significantly impacted by Covid-19, and she missed out on important and potentially life-saving treatment as a result. It also meant she had to endure times travelling and in hospital in the UK alone, due to visiting and travel restrictions in place. Mum’s consultant from Clatterbridge Hospital described her cancer as the “worst case he had ever seen”.

Our lives have been left with a massive void, as our Mum is irreplaceable. She was an exceptionally kind, loving, warm-hearted, generous, selfless woman. Mum was a great advocate for others in her roles in education, the charitable sector and the local Manx community. Her sense of humour is greatly missed, and played a major part in the strength she showed with her illness. No day is the same now she has gone, and we continue to miss her living life with us.  We are hoping to complete the walk on the 1st June 2021, which would have been Mum’s 63rd birthday.

Macmillan offered Mum invaluable support over the phone when she was an inpatient at Whiston Hospital and she rated the advice they gave her highly. It is estimated that the Covid -19 pandemic could lead to a further 35,000 deaths from Cancer. We want to support the good work Macmillan do. Walking from Hunstanton to Mundesley will be no easy feat for us, but we want to raise awareness and funds for Macmillan. 

Please do sponsor us and thank you for visiting our page. 

Catherine, Emily and Ryan x

story:
Me and my wife have decided to try doing the 300,000 steps in March event.

I have vascular problems that prevent me from walking distances and I have to use a 2kg plastic boot to stop the bones in my ankle from snapping due to osteoporosis or brittle bone syndrome. We would like to raise as much as possible for Macmillans cancer support as they have suffered a lot with fundraising due to Covid-19 like the rest of us and we just wanted to try to give back to a support group needed by so many.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
We are doing the Mighty Hike to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support. Our mum was diagnosed late last year with Breast Cancer which was devastating news as she had it 11yrs ago and now it’s come back. Mum is now 83yrs old and we were all very concerned she would not be able to cope with Chemo Theropy at this time. After careful consideration, looking into all the risks involved with it, she decided to go ahead with the treatment. 

After 4 cycles of Chemo Theropy which she coped with incredibly well. She did feel poorly and suffered quite a few side effects, including losing her hair, which was a big thing for my mum as she used to be a hairdresser and her hair always looked immaculate. She got through all this with a lot of help from us, her family and her amazing friends that helped in keeping her spirits up. 

Following the Chemo Theropy, she then went straight into hospital for the surgery on her breast, again she was incredibly brave and took it all in her stride. She has now found she has a  DVT which hopefully will be treated quickly and she can carry on with her recovery.  I admire her so much for her bravery and coping with all this at her age. We would all like to wish her well and this is the reason we would like to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support , whilst doing something fun and healthy at the same time.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Kier Group has selected the British Heart Foundation, the biggest independent funder of cardiovascular research in the UK, as its new corporate charity partner. The two-year partnership will help in the charitys aim of increasing awareness of cardiovascular disease, raise £250,000 for vital research in to heart and circulatory conditions as well as train 1,500 Kier colleagues in the lifesaving first aid, CPR.

The British Heart Foundation is funding life saving research to help end heartbreak for the seven million people in the UK living with cardiovascular disease. For over 50 years it has pioneered research that has transformed the lives of people living with heart and circulatory conditions and has been pivotal to offering vital treatments that are changing the fight against heart disease.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: For the month of March I am taking part in the Step Challenge on behalf of British Heart Foundation. In December 2020 I took ill and thanks to my GP, was quickly referred to the hospital. I had no idea what was wrong but eventually a scan revealed I had heart disease and suffered from a heart attack. Sadly not all the signs are obvious. Thanks to the wonderful team at the Royal Infirmary, they've fixed me up and I'm on the road to recovery. If it wasn't for the vital research of the British Heart Foundation, I don't know how things would have turned out. I've kicked the smoking habit, cut down on the booze, follow a healthy eating plan and have never felt better. Exercise is also a vital part of recovery and I want to give back to such a worthy cause. If you would kindly spare any small donation it would be greatly appreciated. I will post regular updates throughout March x

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Friends and family who truly know me would know my passion for chocolate! Yes I am a chocoholic and now my daughter is too! 

Since this pandemic, chocolate has increased in our household. Being busy (both keyworkers and missing family and friends terribly). 

My daughter and I have started to pick up more unhealthy habits and turned to chocolate on a daily basis..  when tired, bored, happy or when feeling emotional. It is our go to food and want to show her how you can be more in control and eventually just have it every now and then and not on a daily basis! 

Wish us luck! 


The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our Just Giving page in loving memory of our Dad, Richard Ford.

Richard (Dad) was a kind and caring man who put family first and enjoyed living life to the full. Dad was the main driving force behind Ford Fuels and he always used to love visiting customers, most of which he classed as his close Friends. 

Richard enjoyed spending time with his beloved family and many hobbies which included;

- gardening 

- watching Bristol City

- point to point racing 

- fishing on his boat 

- holidaying in Malta with Mum 

- socialising with a pint in his hand

As a family we have chosen the British Heart Foundation as our nominated charity as this relates to the passing of Dad.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
As everyone knows, I love snacking on chocolates, sweets and fizzy drinks and treats!! By giving up these for March, I’m hoping to get healthier and raise money for British Heart Foundation at the same time!! I could have chosen to just give up chocolate and/or sweets but I have decided to test my will power even more and go the full challenge!!


I will try and not get too grumpy at work and home with my lack of sugar haha!!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
It saddens us to announce that our beloved husband, dad, brother, uncle Mr Pravinbhai Panchal, passed away on the 17th February 2021. 

Our dad was a very strong character, who was hardworking and committed to his business. He was blessed to have a supporting wife, two proud children and a son in law who were very precious and close to him.
His caring heart and endless drive to help his family and friends was valued very much. We will never forget the smiles, laughter and great memories he has left us with.

Like a shooting star, flying across the room so fast, so far he was gone too soon 

The family would like to thank you all, near and far, for all your prayers, support and condolences throughout this difficult time. 

Please feel free to donate as much or as little as you wish to raise money for this great charity.


Jai Shree Krishna, Jai Sairam

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi!

I am giving up chocolate for a whole month to raise money for British heart foundation.

I’ve done it before (not for a couple of years) so I can promise that I will find this reallyyy difficult, especially as my fave food is chocolate digestives and I have some form of chocolate at least 2 or 3 times a day (probably more reason to give it up).

It’s even more important this year because bhf had had to cut their research funds in half (see text below), and the research really is vital helping people with all sorts of heart diseases (that’s the technical term), supporting patients, educating medical professionals and developing new treatments.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
I know many people with heart conditions that I hold very close, research has slowed down due to the pandemic and British Heart Foundation need our help now more than ever. This research is so crucial,  it could save someone's life.

I hope I can help by going on a dechox and taking in some donations! It would mean a lot to me because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers.

story:
❤️This will be a challenge for me as I do enjoy the sweet stuff... I might have had two puddings on more than one occasion when my husband politely declined his!  

And from a personal perspective, I would like this to kick-start some healthier lifestyle choices to assist recuperation from CFS/M.E symptoms; rather than wallowing with chocolate 🍫! I will be donating money saved on goodies to the BHF. 

🍬However, if you are someone who would usually gift me an Easter Egg; please still do so, hide it and provide it to me in April! 

❤️BRITISH HEART FOUNDATION❤️

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I am taking part in the March Dechox challenge by having no chocolate, sweets or fizzy drinks for the whole month of March! Those of you that know me well know what a chocoholic I am. So it won't be easy. I wanted to challenge my self as a birthday 'treat' to myself whilst raising vital funds for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi everyone,

As you know, my wonderful, inspiring, one of a kind dad passed away suddenly and unexpectedly in June 2020 of a massive cardiac arrest. There’s a hole now in all of our lived that can never be filled, and I miss him so much every day. 

I would love to complete this challenge set by the British Heart Foundation to raise money for them in his memory. I don’t want anyone else to go through what we’ve had to over the past 8 months, and BHF can help research and support new ways to end heartbreak forever.

I have a massive sweet tooth, but I’m determined! I’m giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks for the whole of March. Not easy during a lockdown! I’d be so grateful for any amount you can spare to help me reach my goal.

Thank you!

Ellie x


The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thank you for visiting Dad’s page.

We are supporting the BHF because Dad had a longstanding heart condition, which due to complications caused by Covid19, contributed to his early death. 

The charity is supported by our wider family circle as we have sadly lost other close family members to heart conditions in the past.

Thank you for choosing to support The British Heart Foundation

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The reason we are taking part in this dechox challenge, is that as you all know me I’m a chocoholic and Brian is very partial to fizzy drinks. So this will be a hard month and may cause a few arguments but not a divorce 😂😂.(fingers crossed) 

We have both lost parents with heart conditions and they both left this world far too early. So we would like to help where we can. 

So we are asking all our friends for a small donation, whether it’s pocket change or notes, all will help this worthy cause.

Thank you it’s means a lot ♥️

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Thank you for your donation. I am raising money for the British Heart Foundation  in memory of my Father-in-law Jack Lawrenson. Jack sadly passed away on 17th February 2021, he was a gentleman and role model to all. Anything you give will go to help others, something Jack was always quick to do. 

Jack Lawrenson RIP.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
An important charity that needs our help at a time when their research budget has been forced to be cut in half.

This is going to be a huge if not impossible challenge.

TYPICAL EVENING IN PANA'S WORLD
A Twirl followed by another Twirl....
followed by 2 bags of Hula Hoops...
followed by a Crunchie...
followed by a Curly Wurly...
And throw in some sweets for good measure..

You get the picture.  
I'm a sofa binger predominately when the other half has nipped out of the room !

So this challenge is most definitely going to help my heart and your donations will most definitely help millions of others.

Every penny counts.
Your support means the world!!

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic has made life difficult for many charities and the British Heart Foundation is one of them. 

My dad ( Tommy) was one of life’s sweet lovers ( he could unwrap a sweet wrapper in his pocket silently so he didn’t have to share them 😆) and therefore it’s appropriate that I accept this challenge in his name (he’d find the whole thing hysterical as I have inherited the sweet gene).

So, if you have a spare pound, get involved and donate  if you can. 

Thank you x. ( What am I doing!!!?)

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: The sudden death of Brian has left his 6 children and 21 grandchildren absolutely distraught! He sadly passed away on the 8/09/2015 due to Heart Disease. Brian was a very hard working man and made sure his children had the best in life. He was a kind, caring and gentle man who loved his family and not a day goes by where we don’t stop and think to ourselves “oh he used to like this” or “ he would have hated this”. My sister and myself are kindly asking for donations to go 31 days in March without chocolate to raise money to support the British Heart Foundation in memory of our grandad who will always be loved and missed! Thank you for your donations🥰

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page in memory of a very special young man Conor James Feeney.

Our son Conor was a patient at Great Ormond Street children's hospital from 3 month's old, up until the age of 16, where Conor had open heart surgery at 5 month's old.

On the 15th July 2012 at the age of 18 Conor suffered a cardiac arrest whilst playing football with his team. 11 days after this tragic event on the 26th July on the advice of the doctors we had to switch off Conor's life support machines.

Our families lives were shattered and would never be the same.

Following Conor's passing we set up the Conor James Feeney Brighter Future Fund fundraising to support Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people.

It is our honour to fundraise in his memory and this is why I will be taking part in the London Triathlon (www.livetotri.co.uk) at the ExCel Centre on the 7th August 2021.

Conor will always live on in the hearts of his family and friends.

 Your generosity is very much appreciated.

Thank you,

John

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
owner: Jodie Kirkham Community Champion Morrisons Bulwell
story:
This March, Morrisons and Marie Curie are working side by side to raise vital funds for frontline nurses to help dying people and their loved ones.

This has been a hard year for everyone. Weve faced challenging times as a nation, and we know it's the small moments that bring people together. Such moments can be made possible for dying people and their loved ones by the expert care of Marie Curie Nurses, who can bring care, comfort and clarity at the very toughest time. 

Your support means the world to people affected by terminal illness.  From picking your daffodil in-store and wearing it with pride, to taking on your own fundraising challenge you're making vital care possible.

Put simply, without the support people like you highly skilled Marie Curie Nurses couldn't continue giving vital care to people living with a terminal illness and their families.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel.
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk.
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

eventName: Beca goes meat-free for a fortnight!
story:
I am a meat loving seven and a half year old and I am raising money for Marie Curie Penarth because they helped my Taid/HPJ when he had had cancer. I used to take the newspaper to Holm Towers every morning and get a coffee for him. Everybody there was lovely and I think they deserve the money.

Not eating meat for two weeks will be a big challenge for me. Taid was vegetarian for 18 years so this is a good challenge in his memory!

Thank you for reading my page.

Love Beca x

eventName: In memory of Jasumati Vasanji Vadgama
story:
It is with great sadness that the Vadgama family inform you of the peaceful passing of our beloved mother & wife of (Late) Vasanji Velji Vadgama.

🙏🏽 Jayshree Krishna from all of the Vadgama family:

  • Kishore & Vasu Vadgama
  • Dilip Vadgama
  • Nita & Naresh Kargathra
  • Dipak & Yashruti Vadgama
  • Patu & Kishore Ambasana
  • Nutan & Subhash Sankadecha
  • Bhashen Vadgama

She was a loving grandmother to twelve grandchildren and seven great-grand children.

All proceeds go directly to the Marie Curie charity. These donations will help for care and support to those with terminal illnesses.

Thanks for taking the time to visit our family JustGiving page.

eventName: Enniskillen Integrated Primary School Walking Around the World to raise funds for Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

In memory of Alex Wilson a dear daddy of Ryan and my own beloved sister Catherine Collins and all who have lost or have been touched by cancer or any other illness requiring the support of Marie Curie.  

We as as school would like to show our appreciation for all the amazing things that Marie Curie do to support families in need at their most vulnerable time by raising funds for this charity.

March is Integrated Education Month so we are going to try to visit every country our Children or their Parents are from.

This virtual challenge will unite our school during lockdown and will encourage everyone to walk in their spare time whilst recording steps. These steps will then be added together and put onto a map and collectively we will walk around the world.

All support will be very much appreciated 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. eventName: Morrisons Perth - Marie Curie Daffodil Appeal
story:
This March, Morrisons and Marie Curie are working side by side to raise vital funds for frontline nurses to help dying people and their loved ones.

This has been a hard year for everyone. Weve faced challenging times as a nation, and we know it's the small moments that bring people together. Such moments can be made possible for dying people and their loved ones by the expert care of Marie Curie Nurses, who can bring care, comfort and clarity at the very toughest time. 

Your support means the world to people affected by terminal illness.  From picking your daffodil in-store and wearing it with pride, to taking on your own fundraising challenge you're making vital care possible.

Put simply, without the support people like you highly skilled Marie Curie Nurses couldn't continue giving vital care to people living with a terminal illness and their families.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
This charity is very personal and holds a special place in my heart and for my family too. 

Marie Curie nurses are only really known by the people who have been around them, and this is why it is so important to raise money for them to continue their work. 

These nurses work 24 hours a day, on call and ready for anything, they're extremely compassionate and understanding. By researching and reading about them I'm sure you'll get the jist of what they do exactly.

I truly appreciate everyone's donations and thank you all for visiting my page.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thank you for making a donation to the Marie Curie Nurses in memory of Ann Reid. 

Ann received exceptional care and the family support in the final days of her life from the Marie Curie nurses. They were with Ann and us as a family at the end and ensured that she was not just without pain but truly held and seen by nurses with experience and compassion. 

We were and are so grateful for the care they gave her and the way that they reassured us and looked after us as well. 

We would like these donations to be a mark of our thanks to them and a way of remembering Ann who was throughout her life so caring, compassionate and present to her friends, family and all that she met. 

Thank you. 

Sarah, John and Andrew

story:
Hey guys,

Thanks for looking at my page. As all my friends know I like the occasional beverage or two!. I've decided to give up alcohol for the month of March. I thought what better way to give me a motivational boost then to raise money for a very well deserving charity! 

Marie Curie do amazing work for people with terminal illnesses and end of life care.

So if you can spare the odd pound or two, it would be much appreciated. To make the challenge even more difficult i'll give up chocolate at the same time!! 

Wish me Luck!!

Al Mcilwain

story:
For Marie Curie our Great Daffodil Appeal month of March is normally full of some wonderful fundraising & fabulous support and this year we need your help more than ever before. With no collections in supermarkets, daffodil pins in shops & businesses or face to face events, we really do need you to help us reach all corners of our communities, to give everyone the chance to donate and get their virtual daffodil. Our nurses have never been busier as all health care professionals strive to keep patients at home for their care. Please donate to our virtual collection so that we can continue to help care for our patients and support their families through such a difficult & emotional time.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story: Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. I'm walking in memory of three great men, the first was my lovely Husband who was cruelly taken at only 23, brave and courageous throughout he died of a bone tumour, Marie Curie Nurses were there for me throughout and being only 23 myself I couldn't have coped without them. They were there when as a young woman I felt lonely and desperate. The second person is my amazing Dad, my best friend, guide and advisor and an exceptional Father. He died in 2013 of cancer, he died with dignity and never complained. He missed out on seeing his Great Grandchildren whom he would have adored. The last person I am walking in memory of is my lovely Father-In-Law, Ken, you couldn't help but love him, he always had a smile and a famous whistle. Another great man who never complained. I think most of us in our lives will be affected by cancer in some way, I know from experience that Marie Curie Nurses really do make a difference and this is a small thing I do to raise funds, the difference they make is huge.
title: In memory of Paul, Dad  Ken

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Hi everyone! We're taking part in Marie Curie’s Step into Spring 2021 Challenge and will be walking 10,000 steps every day in March to raise money for this amazing charity. We will never forget the support and care they gave to our wonderful Grandma Pat and to us during her final months. We can never thank enough the nurses who spent the night in an uncomfortable arm chair, keeping our Pat company whilst awake and safe while she slept. By doing this, they not only gave Gail, Michael and Susan a break, but they also allowed Pat to stay in her own home for much longer. Any donations would be greatly appreciated to enable them to carry on helping other families like they did ours♥






Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
eventName: Andy's 60 days till my 60th birthday weight loss challenge (  Supporting  the RNLI )
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

My sister Mabel and I recently watched an episode of The Perfect Planet and were really concerned by what we saw. We want to help save the animals living on our planet for us to enjoy for years to come. 

We have decided to raise money for WWF to help this fantastic cause by climbing (using any staircase we can find) the equivalent of the height of Mount Everest over the next few weeks. That’s just 17475 stairs folks. 

We are very excited to start the challenge and hope you will help us reach our target for this amazing charity.

Thanks for reading 

Love Emily xx

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

We can all do our bit to help out, whether it be raising money to help organisations like the WWF or cutting down on our carbon footprint. Cycling to work and to meet people rather then driving can be a good way to lower the impact and also improve your health, so a double benefit! 

To prove that you can get a lot further on a bicycle then you may think, I will be attempting to break the world record for the furthest cycled in a month. This is currently heald at 7031 miles, but to prove my point I will be attempting to add and extra 2000 miles and completing 9000 miles in a month. 

Now not everyone can physically ride that far and don't worry you don't have too! But I want to prove its possible and in doing so hopefully make that 5 mile ride to work seem less daunting. 

Not all of us are directly feeling the effects of climate change but our wildlife are. Our choices are destroying their habitats and the places they call home. Just because we're top of the food change doesn't mean we need to abuse it. Understandly though we don't truly know how our individual choices stack up to cause these terrible circumstances, me being on of them. 

But its time we all take a look at ourselves and ask the question what we can all do to help. I'm hoping that by completely this incredible challenge I've taken on will help to raise this awareness and encourage everyone to leave the car at home and walk or ride to our local destination. 

Thank you for taking the time to read my story and hope you find it in your heart to donate to this wonderful cause which is doing wonderful things across the world to save our wildlife! We will all thank ourselves in the future!

story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

Your support is much appreciated.

Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Hi!

As well as being dark, cold and miserable, another depressing thing about winter is that it reveals exactly how much rubbish people have thrown out of their car windows when passing by our lovely village.  To celebrate spring's near-arrival, Celia and I are going to spend a day taking it in turn with our litter-pickers (whilst the other one entertains Peggy and Mabel!) to get rid of all the nasty stuff from alongside our bit of the A433, as well as any that may be in the village itself. 

Now I've done it in the past for free and will gladly do so again in the future, but I thought just this once it might be a good to use the opportunity to raise some money.  Unicef work to help the most vulnerable children in the world and I hope you'll join us in pledging some money to help support their work.  Any amount would be gratefully received!

I'm sure we all agree how lucky we are to live in such a gorgeous part of the country!

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story: In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 2021 is a vital year in the global campaign to make our world one without malaria. This coming June, the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and the vitally important Kigali Summit on malaria and neglected tropical diseases will take place in Rwanda. The summit marks a historic moment that will unite global leaders and put a spotlight on the importance of renewed action in fighting malaria. We need more action, more innovation, more funding and more political leadership to defeat malaria and move forward stronger in this new global health landscape. Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will ‘reach’ the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UN’s World Malaria Day on 25 April. Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every £1 raised up to £100,000.” Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation. Please show your support.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
